Volvamos a los modelos lineales

data("mtcars")
Modelo1 <- lm(mpg ~ wt, data = mtcars)

\[ \begin{aligned} \operatorname{\widehat{mpg}} &= 37.29 - 5.34(\operatorname{wt}) \end{aligned} \]

  • Mas de una variable
data("mtcars")
Modelo2 <- lm(mpg ~ wt + hp, data = mtcars)

\[ \begin{aligned} \operatorname{\widehat{mpg}} &= 37.23 - 3.88(\operatorname{wt}) - 0.03(\operatorname{hp}) \end{aligned} \]

  • wt = 3, hp = 150
37.23 - 3.88 * 3 - 0.03 * 150
## [1] 21.09

Tambien para variables categricas

mt <- mtcars %>%
    mutate(am = ifelse(am == 0, "Automatic", "Manual"))

Modelo3 <- lm(mpg ~ am, data = mt)

\[ \begin{aligned} \operatorname{\widehat{mpg}} &= 17.15 + 7.24(\operatorname{am}_{\operatorname{Manual}}) \end{aligned} \]

  • \({am}_{Manual}\) en una variable binaria, si am es = “Manual” es 1, si no es 0
  • Si un auto es manual entonces:
17.15 + 7.24 * 1
## [1] 24.39
  • Si un auto es automtico entonces:
17.15 + 7.24 * 0
## [1] 17.15

O ambas

Modelo4 <- Modelo3 <- lm(mpg ~ am + wt, data = mt)

\[ \begin{aligned} \operatorname{\widehat{mpg}} &= 37.32 - 0.02(\operatorname{am}_{\operatorname{Manual}}) - 5.35(\operatorname{wt}) \end{aligned} \]

  • am = “automatico”, wt = 3
37.32 - 0.02 * 0 + 5.35 * 3
## [1] 53.37
  • am = “manual”, wt = 3
37.32 - 0.02 * 0 + 5.35 * 3
## [1] 53.37

Formula lm con interacciones

Supongamos que tenemos dos variables \(X_1\) categorica e \(X_2\) es continua

  • \(C_0\) Intercepto
  • \(C_1\) modificador de intercepto para nivel 1
  • \(\beta_1\) pendiente de argumento 1

\[y = \beta_1X_1 + \beta_2X_2 + \beta_3X_1X_2 + C_0 + C_1\]
